<subSubSection id="23B9656B9B1FFF8A9FE1FDA3FD6C9088" pageId="17" pageNumber="130" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6B1C36E09B1FFF8A9FE1FDA3FD6C9088" blockId="17.[151,1437,152,713]" pageId="17" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="59D7EAF29B1FFF8A9FE1FDA3FEE19022" bold="true" box="[199,315,585,611]" pageId="17" pageNumber="130">Remarks.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="B41888429B1FFF8A9E5DFDA3FE019022" box="[379,475,585,611]" pageId="17" pageNumber="130">paratype</typeStatus>
female specimens were identified as conspecific with the 
<typeStatus id="B41888429B1FFF8A9BA3FDA3FB3D9022" box="[1157,1255,585,611]" pageId="17" pageNumber="130">holotype</typeStatus>
male specimen #06472 by morphological similarity, though the body color pattern of #06472 rather indistinct than females. Considering the insufficiency of evidence of species-level divergence between the 
<typeStatus id="B41888429B1FFF8A9CD8FD60FBBA90E5" box="[1022,1120,650,676]" pageId="17" pageNumber="130">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="B41888429B1FFF8A9BB2FD61FB2E90E4" box="[1172,1268,651,677]" pageId="17" pageNumber="130">paratype</typeStatus>
specimens, we tentatively describe them as of the same species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
